\section{Date arithmetic produces year-50,888 timestamps}{

\strong{Symptom:} \code{mutate(ts = as.POSIXct(date, origin = "1970-01-01"))}
produces timestamps in the year 50,888.

\strong{Cause:} The \code{date} column is bigint Unix epoch in \emph{milliseconds}, not
seconds. R's \code{as.POSIXct()} expects seconds.

\strong{Fix:} Use \code{\link[=clean_dates]{clean_dates()}} or divide by 1000 manually:
\code{mutate(ts = clean_dates(date))}.
}

\section{Join produces zero matched rows between chat and streams}{

\strong{Symptom:} \code{inner_join(chat, streams, by = "channel")} returns zero
rows even though both tables have data for the same streamers.

\strong{Cause:} \code{chat$channel} is prefixed with \verb{#} (IRC convention);
\code{streams$channel} is not.

\strong{Fix:} In the shipped \link{twitch_chat_sample}, the prefix has been
stripped, so the join works as-is. If you are pulling raw data from the
source dump, normalize first:
\code{mutate(channel = sub("^#", "", channel))}.
}

\section{\code{setup()} reports Quarto missing but I have Quarto installed}{

\strong{Symptom:} \code{v2v::setup()} shows a red x on Quarto CLI even though you
can run Quarto from the terminal.

\strong{Cause:} The R \code{quarto} package is not installed. R looks up the CLI
through that wrapper.

\strong{Fix:} \code{install.packages("quarto")} and run \code{setup()} again.
}

\section{Cohen's kappa is much lower than I expected}{

\strong{Symptom:} Two coders who seem to agree most of the time still
produce a kappa near 0.20.

\strong{Cause:} Kappa corrects for chance agreement. If one code is rare,
two coders can agree 90\% of the time on the \emph{common} code (negative)
and still produce a low kappa because the agreement on the \emph{rare} code
(positive) is the load-bearing signal.

\strong{Fix:} Two paths: (1) revise the codebook so the rare code is better
defined and shows up more often, or (2) report Krippendorff's alpha
(\code{method = "alpha"}) which handles imbalance more gracefully.
}

\section{\code{data(twitch_chat_sample)} returns NULL or "not found"}{

\strong{Symptom:} \code{data(twitch_chat_sample)} throws "data set
'twitch_chat_sample' not found".

\strong{Cause:} The package is not installed, or you are calling \code{data()}
without \code{library(v2v)} first.

\strong{Fix:} \code{library(v2v)} and try again. If still failing, reinstall:
\code{install.packages("v2v")} or
\code{remotes::install_github("SIM-Lab-SIUE/v2v")}.
}

